segments.text: be they performers or speakers or politicians who made appearances on campus?
Well, as I was just talking about Town Hall, I remember that Ray Armstrong and his band came here.
Ray Anthony.
Ray Anthony, you're right, Ray Anthony.
And a couple of singers, it seemed like one of them's name was Cummings.
Charles Lawton came and had readings.
Yeah.
I remember that very well because it came time for the performance.
Spike White, who was head of student activities, well, part of student activities and head of all that business, came around and told us, we've got a real problem.
What's the problem?
Mr. White said, well, Mr. Lawton says he's not going to perform tonight.
We've got the whole down hall filled with people.
Well, he's paid here to come.
Well, he's not feeling too well.
But they finally convinced him to go out about 30 minutes later, and he put on a magnificent performance.
So that kind of thing sort of sticks in my mind.
All right, the other thing, talking about who came, Rod Eisenhower came a couple times when I was here on the campus.
One, well, mainly he came to inaugurate
Dr. Harrington was president of the university.
Guyon Hall, what role did it play as a facility in student life?
Guyon Hall was an assembly hall at the end, at the south end of Middle Cary Walk, located about where Rudder Tower is now.
And it was the place where we had various assemblies.
When we had religious emphasis week, that's where those that wanted to go, that's where the speakers were.
on cultural kind of things like I was just mentioning.
That's where the performances were.
It was the largest place on campus in the form of an auditorium kind of thing.
And movies.
That was used.
And then, yeah, movies, you're right.
On campus, the movies that were given on campus were shown in Grand Hall.
Please describe Religious Emphasis Week as you remember it.
Well, that was a week set aside.
I remember particularly my senior year, the people that came, but we had three or four excellent speakers that came.
One was a chaplain from Washington, D.C., one was a minister from Dallas, and several others.
And they just, they would have main speeches, they would have a number of
sort of workshops where we talked about various things, different topics.
It was an affair that lasted a whole week.
I thought it was an excellent program.
G. Raleigh, was it built?
G. Raleigh White?
That's a blank in my memory.
G. Raleigh White apparently was being built when I was here on the campus.
Whether it opened by the time I left tonight, I don't really remember that at all.
It's just blank.
Where was commencement held?
Where'd you graduate?
I think we graduated from Kyle Peel.
Do you, can you describe what commencement was?
You know, I'm sort of blank on that.
I remember a commission, we had a commission
Ceremony in Gine Hall.
In Gine.
But I think we were too big for Gine, and I don't know necessarily, I'm blank on T. Raleigh White.
We may have had the commencement in there, but it seemed like it was kind of people.
Was the commissioning speaker some notable, famous person?
I don't remember any.
So it wasn't Dwight Eisenhower or somebody like that, you would.
No.
What were the major student activity groups, MSC Council and what else?
Well, it was Corps of Cadets, which at that time still was the main organization here on the campus.
It was the MSC Council.
There were various clubs, hometown clubs.
There were radio clubs, photography clubs, various things.
What about singing cadets?
There was singing cadets.
There was a band, and like today, they've
played for the games during the fall, but during the spring they sort of played a different kind of music.
Where's that?
I'm not asking now if you were a member.
Were there, as far as you know, any secret fraternities then?
There apparently were, because I remember my junior year, a number of cadets got in trouble for
At least the authorities thought they belonged to the secret organization.
And at that time, that was against the universal rules.
What were the names or name of those?
The only name I remember was called the TTs or the True Texans.
And I've since heard about swastikas and stickers or whatever, but that may be all the same thing.
I don't know.
Let's see.
And they, as far as you know, what was their purpose?
I don't know.
I don't really know.
Let's see, project houses, were they still in use in those days?
Those houses down at Southgate that had been built during the Depression for... No, at the Southgate, when I was a student here, what I remember is they were...
They were married students' houses.
A series of them all looked alike, and they were there until not too long ago.
Now, what's just now been torn down the police station was originally a project house, but I don't remember what it was when I was here.
Let's see.
There were still some veterans here on the campus when you...
There were a number of veterans, and...
They didn't have to be in the Corps, but there were a number in my graduating petroleum engineering class.
We had, I guess, eight or ten veterans.
Did you all think of them as old students?
I suppose we probably did early on, but once we got to know them and by the time we were in our fourth year of graduating, or fifth year, they were just part of the class.
What role did international events play in your thoughts about life after graduation?
In my own particular thoughts, very little.
I don't remember too much about it.
The international events that were impacting, I guess, were like the Korean War.
I joined the National Guard when I was in high school.
And after my freshman year here,

summer of 1950 we were at summer camp and we thought we were going to never come home from summer camp but that didn't turn out that way but that would be the international kind of event and then as I went into the when I got an advanced contract in the Air Force I had to drop out of the National Guard because I was in the Army at that time but you know we thought about in terms of conflicts overseas and that kind of thing that's where we might go
as far as going into business, so I didn't give it much thought.
Did A&M help you with summer jobs?
The A&M did one year.
See, I guess that was after my freshman year.
Again, I went to .
My dad had died, and my mother had moved to Austin.
And I didn't know anybody in Austin,
be home for the summer and work.
I had to work.
So I went to Mr. McQuillan again and asked him if he thought that Mr. Wynne could help me get a job in Austin.
And should I write him?
He said, well, let me just take care of that for you.
And it turned out that that's what happened.
He cut word back to go see a couple of people in Austin.
went out and put me to work with a moving company, working all summer, which is great.
Now, what routine did you and other students have for going home or other places on weekends when you didn't have a car?
We had a great hitchhiking system that had developed over the years at A&M, and we used it extensively if you wanted to go anywhere.
I wanted to go anywhere at least for the first two or three years because I didn't have a car.
I didn't know anybody with a car.

and the system was most anywhere you went there was a certain spot that had been selected and like out at the annex you'd go out to the main gate on highway 21 and if you if you were heading west you were okay because if you were you got a ride you could keep that ride but if you're going east you had to hitchhike in the brown and then in the direction from there you had to go the aggie hitchhiking place
And where was that in Bryan?
I don't remember exactly where it was.
I never really early on went that direction, but it must have been about where Highway 21 and Highway 6 cross, not the new bypass, but the old Highway 6.
Once you got to the camp?
Once you got to that hitchhiking place, then there was a protocol that you went through.
In the first place, you knew you were going to be at the end of the line because that was in the album.
But you went up to the man that was first in line, and you met everybody all the way down the line.
And then you took your place.
But it didn't go by classes.
It went by who got there, first come, first serve kind of thing.
And if you were in line and four seniors came up behind you, that was OK.
They wouldn't go to bunk you out of line.
Where, from the main campus, where was that hitchhiking location?
Out of what we called the East Gate.
On that time, Highway 6, the bypass wasn't here, so we went out to the main gate and drove south and north.
That's where we were going.
What did you wear and what gear did you take with you hitchhiking?
Well, the best thing to wear if you were hitchhiking was a uniform, because people anywhere, if they saw an Aggie standing on the road hitchhiking, they'd pick him up.
And usually, I took very little gear.
I had a little shaving kit, a toothbrush, and cestas in there, and maybe a little small bag with a change of clothes.
That was about it.
Let's see, how did an Aggie get a date?
Get her to and from the campus and so forth?
Sometimes wonder about that.
The way you got dates, well, obviously people that you knew,
mainly to meet other girls and so on through friends.
We were going to another town like my freshman year.
I didn't have a roommate in the barracks because there were 20 of us, I think, in one barracks, but we had bunkmates.
We had double-decker bunks and so my bunkmate was a fellow from Waco and when we went on a court trip to Waco, obviously he got me and several other people mates with friends of his.
So that was the main way we met people.
If girls were coming to the campus, they would either come by bus or train.
They were coming from a distance, or some of them, if they had friends.
A lot of them, like, if they were coming from Austin, would more than likely come with friends that had college.
So it was a little difficult to get Austin over here by bus.
Where did they stay here?
They stayed all over the place.
with faculty members, with anybody that you knew that you could get a room.
A lot of people would rent rooms on weekends.
Did you ever hear of moose pots and beast buckets?
No, I don't think so.
Those terms would be used later.
You and your buddies would have blind dates with a group of girls.
Yeah, okay.
And there would be a pot here as to which one got stuck with the worst one.
They, meanwhile, would have
and I'd forgotten which was male and which was female, and each group thought they were the only ones worried about getting stuck.
I don't remember those particular terms, but there were other terms.
Now, on a Saturday night, if an Aggie had a date, where would he take her?
To what kind of place or event?
Normally, the reason you'd bring a date here to the campus was because there was a dance or something like that that you were bringing her here for.
other than that people would go to their hometown or wherever the date was and have a date there.
Please describe one of those dances.
Well the one I remember the most I guess was military ball my senior year and that was military weekend so there were a number of distinguished people here on the campus.
The ranking officer that came down was General McCullough
famous in World War II, Battle of the Bulge time, for saying nuts to the Germans.
But they were, I remember going out to Eastwood when they came flying in on a converted B-17 that had been made to a transport, and they must have been about 20 people or so that came in.
So that was, the ball was just part of the overall weekend, where we had a lunch and a parade and
The combat ball had been the night before.
So it was a big weekend.
So where was that dance held?
The dance, like normal, was held in Sevesa where they would clear out all the tables and everything and have a big floor for dancing.
And what did people wear?
The cadets would wear their uniforms and the girls usually had on their evening gowns and the finery that they had brought with them.
Big bands?
We had, for that military ball, I'm sure it was the Aggieland orchestra that played.
I'm not absolutely sure of that.
But there was an orchestra, which we didn't mention earlier.
Describe the community of College Station that surrounded the campus.
What was here, and where was it?
There wasn't a whole lot around College Station.
The north gate area was the central.
If you went off campus for businesses, and if you didn't go downtown Bryan, then the Northgate area was essentially where the businesses were.
There were housing that a number of the factory lived in to the south.
Those homes are still there.
To the east of Eastgate, the older part of that was there at the time.
And a number of the factory that I knew, two of them
two of my petroleum professors lived over there.
When I was a graduate student here, we rented, two friends of mine and I rented an apartment over near the East Gate.
We used to go off campus to a Mexican restaurant.
It was somewhere over about the Chimney Hill area.
Maybe not quite that far, but, you know, that, it wasn't that far to drive, but it was sort of far out as far as it was concerned.
It was sort of beyond the houses and
That's what I thought so.
What businesses were at Northgate?
Lippox had a bookstore there.
The campus theater was there and operating very well as a movie theater.
I mean, it was a nice place to go.
I can't remember the name, but the university bookstore was there.
Later branched out to those places and called it a station.
I think that photography shop on the corner was there.
The boot shop was there.
And a photographer came under name back on old college back off of the University block or two and was in there, still there I think.
I haven't been in there in a number of years.
That's about all I can remember.
Must have been a couple of eating places, though.
If you and I came by bus, where did we arrive and depart?
Where was the bus station for College Station?
I don't remember.
I think it was Eastgate.
What about the railroad?
Well, the railroad is where the railroad is now, but the depot was right opposite the Grove in that area.
That's the best way of describing it.
and the creamery was nearby.
Where, if you and I wanted to get an alcoholic beverage, where could we have gotten a drink?
Well, for an old German from Brunham, they'd say this, but I don't really remember trying to find an alcoholic drink around here.
I think I drank something when we'd go off on weekends to Houston or whatever.
I drank beer or whatever, but I don't remember
particularly searching for any around here.
But there was the famous Whiskey Bridge out off of Highway, what is that, 50?
Going west on the campus, University Extension.
As far as I know, that was legal and everything.
Yeah, that was legal.
That was over in Burleson County, which is, having had to be of age.
Let's see, were there any...
I can't think of any campus, big campus catastrophes, fires, or anything like that.
There were no big campus events during your five years here, were there?
No catastrophes like that that I can recall.
At the inauguration of Dr. Harrington, were there any other big, special, one-of-a-kind events?
The opening of the MSC was a big
and Dr. Harrington's inauguration.
Before I left here, before I graduated, Dr. Morgan, the president, I don't recall that there was an inauguration ceremony for him.
I guess maybe Dr. Harrington's was the one.
We had
We had our problems.
I was Colonel of the Corps my senior year, and it seemed like there was a problem every week of some sort or another.
I didn't know that.
So describe for me the process of going from the annex to becoming Corps Commander.
When did you begin to realize you might have that potential and so forth?
Well, you know, looking back on it,
It was quite interesting.
I didn't, you know, I came here from a tiny school and was awed by all these worldly people from Houston and places like that.

And while I became really dear friends with three or four guys from Dallas, we started out in the barracks out there in Phoenix together and went to the unit that I mentioned earlier, Squadron 10 and the Corps together.

And I guess, you know, in my sophomore year in Squadron 10, toward the end of the year, when people were being picked for positions the coming year, when I was asked if I wanted to go into the Corps of Staff.
And, you know, that was an honor.
So, yeah, sure, I did.
And then, I don't remember now, there were six or eight juniors that were put on the Coast Staff.
I mean, as juniors who were on the Coast Staff.
Maybe more, but I think about eight.
And I didn't really expect to be a Corps Commander.
I just thought, well, I'd go there and get that experience.
And then maybe my senior year, I'd probably not go back to be a unit commander.
There'd probably be a staff commander, or wing, or battalion, or something like that.
I couldn't say battalion, too.
We didn't have battalions in the Air Force.
But we rotated, being what was called a sergeant major, the chief junior in the corps.
And I was about the third or fourth one to rotate.
I forget now how long we kept that job, about six weeks or something.
During my rotation, I felt like I'd done a good job, and I felt like I was doing as well and maybe better than a couple of the others that I'd fought early on.
Anyway, I don't know how it all happened.
I was really surprised in the end.
We went through, I don't recall exactly what it was, but we went before panels.
Back in that time, as opposed to today, today people put their own name in if they want to.
want that job, which was fine.
Back at that time, we didn't, you know.
People would, you know, I don't know how I was picked to be, to go before the panel.
But anyway, I remember the interviews with some of the other cadets, seniors, and a number of the military officers on the panel, and talking to them, answering questions, and that kind of thing.
And I guess, you know, in the end, I was surprised to be the one that was picked.
And I'm assuming then as a senior you were part of the screening review group.

As you now think of it from both sides of having been selected and having been one of those who would later help make the next selection, what were the key qualities that you think they were looking for?
Certainly leadership, because that's a key thing.

But a good part of leadership is personality, being able to get along with people, and not being able to leave without getting everybody all upset about what orders you have to give, that kind of thing.
Academics certainly play the role, because this is an academic institution, and you don't necessarily want to pick a guy that's just about to bunk out.
But I remember the fellow that followed me, who was picked, was on the poor staff also when I was a senior.
You know, he was obviously of that group of juniors, the one that could do the best job.
Do you think geography, parentage, family income played any part?
Geography certainly didn't.
My family income when I was here had no part at all.
And parentage, of course, parentage does have a big role.
Oh, no, but I mean the fact that you were Germanic or rich or poor.
No, no, no.
But the way your parents raised you and all that has tremendous .
Of course.
That was the thing that always impressed me about A&M.
And in fact, it was one of the reasons that I, even before I got the opportunity or the scholarship to come here, that I was leaning toward A&M.
Because I had been told some things about Texas University.
And I had been told that if you go to A&M, you make it strictly on your own merit.
It doesn't matter.
And I saw that in action because in my barracks at the annex
of a very wealthy man in Houston, a very, very big Aggie, and we all knew that early on, but you know, and I became great friends with him, but that had absolutely nothing to do with anything else.
He got kidded some, we all got kidded about something early, so he was strictly on the
and what you yourself could do.
And I hope it's still that way.
It is still your target.
Let's stay with your senior year as Corps Commander.
Describe a typical week's routine for the Corps Commander your senior year.
Well, I think the main part of it was sort of the early few weeks getting started, getting things, I wouldn't say necessarily organized,

because all of the cadet leaders had been picked and they were in place and all that, but it still takes a little bit for an organization to get functioning, getting used to each other, and getting used to your new role and that kind of thing.
We had new freshmen on campus, getting all that going.
Once beyond that, it became sort of a routine.
You're all, your classes, you're still taking a, you know, in those days you took a heavy load of classes.
I finished building a degree in four years, and I think I finished with about 156 hours.
So I was taking 18, 19, 20 hours.
And so had that go.
Sort of typical was during the day, no particular problem.
We were early morning formation, get our meal, go back to our room.
We had a class, which you usually get fairly early, going off to class.
It was after the classes where things really happened.
A lot of core activities, always late in the afternoon.
The units are practicing their marching, their drills, doing various things.
Part of the military science classes are various labs.
But as corps commander in the evenings, there were a number of people that generally stopped by.
particularly right after we'd have our evening meal.
They'd come over to my room and they had either something that, some bright idea that they wanted to try out or some gripe that they had about something or other.
Some of them wouldn't even wait that long.
They'd come up to the table.
At that time, we served family style in Duncan.
And so each unit had its own tables and the core staff sat at one particular table.
Two tables, I guess, there in one place.
And so everybody knew where we were.
We'd take care of some of the business during the meal.
Do you remember any particular incident or problem you had to cope with?

You know, it's funny what sticks in your mind or pops back, but a kid, a good friend of mine, every time I see him now, because it sort of saved my, I wouldn't say my skin, but it saved embarrassment.
At one point, we were eating, and
I was sitting at the head of the table, and he was just to my right, so our legs were so close together.
This senior friend of mine came up, and he was, I was Air Force, and the previous corps commander had been Air Force out of the same unit.
And this guy came over with the drive, and this was, I don't know, this was well into the fall semester, way past everything happening, but he just
said, well then it's not right, but Corps Commander, two years in a row, out of the Air Force, out of the same unit.
Or out of the Army, and so on.
And he said something else, which I don't really remember now exactly what happened, but it sort of irritated me, and I started to stand up and argue with him.
And when I started to go up, my friend to my right jammed my legs, and I couldn't get up.
It made me sit back down, and so I sort of, that broke my tension.
I almost had to laugh.
So I just sort of said, oh, you know, Jimmy, forget about it.
We're going back here.
So, you know, things like that.
But it's a great learning experience.
Really a tremendous learning experience.
So you didn't have any hazing, nothing caught fire?
We had hazing incidents.
We had one unit shut down early on.
One unit actually disbanded.
What did they do?
They were hazing.
They had a board, I think.
And I know that was a learning experience, particularly for the unit commander at that time.
Unfortunately, he should have learned a little earlier.
But he and several people came over to the Corps staff area and said, well, you've got to help.
What's the problem?
Well, we're being disbanded.
Well, what happened?
Well, they caught us with a bullet.
What can I do?
What do you think I can do about that?
Well, you've got to help.
I said, listen, there's nothing I can do.
You guys knew the rules.
